{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772048166,"nonce":"Pi1suF68iJ0x7G1+cEhNUjf53fM=","title":"Include muscle activation dynamics in the `AbstractMuscle`, not the `AbstractPlant` instance","message":"[Imported from GitHub #34] (created 2024-03-04T17:48:42Z)\n\nSee #29 for an review of the structure of `AbstractPlant`, and how dynamical updates are aggregated. I'll try to summarize the relevant aspects, here.\n\n[`MuscledArm`](https://github.com/mlprt/feedbax/blob/3768360995fd2d2a71f80f930240518acd6bef5a/feedbax/mechanics/plant.py#L252) has a field `activator`, which is an `AbstractDynamicalSystem` that describes how a muscle's activation changes with its input. For example, we could use a first-order filter to smooth out the input to the muscle, as an approximation of the dynamic of calcium diffusion through a muscle fibre in response to activity at a neuromuscular junction. \n\nThe `activator` component is included in the `dynamics_spec` of `MuscledArm`, which is a subclass [`AbstractPlant`](https://github.com/mlprt/feedbax/blob/3768360995fd2d2a71f80f930240518acd6bef5a/feedbax/mechanics/plant.py#L54); all the components defined in `dynamics_spec` are automatically aggregated into a single `vector_field` method that is used as the `ODETerm` to a Diffrax solver.\n\n**Conceptually, it makes more sense for the muscle activation dynamics to be part of the muscle model -- i.e. `AbstractMuscle`.** However, `AbstractMuscle` is only a subclass of `AbstractStagedModel`, and only defines a sequence of kinematic updates, and no vector fields.\n\nTo fix this, I think **`AbstractMuscle` will have to subclass `AbstractDynamicalSystem`** as well as `AbstractStagedModel`, similarly to the inheritance pattern already used by `AbstractPlant`. \n\nThis should reduce confusion between \"muscle input\" and \"muscle activation\". According to the above description, it's *activation* that's passed as the `input` argument to an `AbstractMuscle`. In some cases however, we might omit the activation filter, and pass a neural network's output directly through `AbstractPlant`, to `AbstractMuscle`.","files":null}]}